MARK 23
The HK Mark 23 Caliber .45 ACP pistol gives shooters match grade accuracy equal to that of the finest custom made handguns — yet exceeds the most stringent operational requirements ever demanded of a combat handgun.

The Mark 23 provides this accuracy without the need for hand-fitted parts common in custom-built match pistols costing thousands of dollars more.

One of the most thoroughly tested handguns in history, the MK23/Mark 23 project originated in 1991 when HK began development for the U.S. Special Operations Command, the organization that directs the activities of America's most elite military units, including the Navy SEALs and the Army Special Forces.

On May 1, 1996, the first HK MK 23 pistols were delivered to the U.S. Special Operations Command for operational deployment, making the MK 23 the first caliber .45 ACP pistol to enter American military service since the venerable Government Model 1911A1.

During testing, MK 23 pistols met the most stringent operational and accuracy requirements ever demanded of a combat handgun. Endurance testing demonstrated a service life of over 30,000 rounds of +P ammunition. To meet the reliability requirement, the pistol had to demonstrate a minimum of 2,000 mean rounds between stoppages (MRBS) with both M1911 ball and +P ammunition. All pistols exceeded the 2000 MRBS with an average of 6000 MRBS. In more than 450 accuracy test firings from a precision firing fixture at 25 meters, MK 23 pistols far exceeded the government requirement, averaging 1.44 inches, with 65 groups of less than one inch. There were four groups of .5 inches, with 5 rounds going through the same hole!

title: For Sale:  Imperial German lion head, Italiian Swords
postcontent:
Imperial German Officer's Jawless Lion Head Sword: - $300
Manufactured by E F Horster.
Unsharpened blade is in excellent shape with no rust, nicks or other damage.
Blade is not etched and is 29" long. The overall length with the scabbard is 35.5"
Nickel metal scabbard showing some rust spots. Double hanger indicates it was issued prior to 1906
The grip is sharkskin with a little wear and the wire wrap is tight with no breaks.
The brass handguard has some tarnish but is still shiny under the portapee.
The portapee appears green and gold to me under the protected areas.

Italian Carabinieri Sword - $200
The only makers mark is a CA. It is on the right side of the blade just at the hilt.
These swords were issued by Italy up to the start of WWII.
Also known as a Hussars or Briquet sword. It is a French pattern 1816 sword.
There is some rust spots on the blade but, it is in good shape.
The unsharpened blade is 23.5" long and the overall length with scabbard is 29.75"
The leather scabbard is in very good plus condition with no splitting or tears. 
The Brass hilt and brass on the scabbard have some tarnish.

I've tried to do my homework on these but take any information provided with a grain of salt, I am not an expert.
Both swords were war trophies along with several firearms from a WWII veteran who recently passed away.
I've shown both sword to military collectors in the area. About the only thing they can agree on is the top sword is Imperial German.

Not looking for any trades, but I will deal if you want to purchase both swords and the bayonet.

 I can provide more and larger photos.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg 46B
location: Northern Fort Wayne, Fort Wayne, Indiana
postcontent: I have a Mossberg 46B I wouldn't mind getting rid of so I can get something else. I took it to my local gun shop and they told me it was the 4th one made. In 1938 Mossberg began making 46B's, and at this time weren't required to serialize them. But the first 10 made were actually manufactured at the end of 1937. Mine is stamped with "No. 4  1937". The guy at the shop offered me $800 and I should've taken it, but held on to it, and it's just taking up room. I'm not asking for $800, but know this is a rare find. Don't offer me $200, I won't respond. And if you want to be a smart ass, or think you know everything about guns don't bother me. Go to a gun shop, ask them about these guns and see how much they know.. very little. There is barely any literature on these guns. Email me or text: REDACTED to make an offer. The bottom gun in the picture is the 46B.

title: For Sale:  Browning Sweet 16, 26" VR Exibition Wood, WOW!!
postcontent: An A5 Sweet 16 for the person who wants one very unique and spectacular example of this model gun! Professionally and meticulously restored Sweet 16, SN X21389 which dates it to the last half of 1948. This almost flawless example of the Sweet 16, was made the first year that they were marked as such. Browning was hand fitting these A5 during that time, with all parts matched, numbered and hand polished to the specific receiver. In addition, this gun has been stocked with a most stunning piece of French walnut, expertly shaped, fitted, checkered and finished. It was made to be EXACTLY like the original, except for the factory Browning marked recoil pad. There is one tiniest of blemishes on the forend, and some minor gold plating wear, off of the trigger and safety. The barrel is 26 inch vent rib with unaltered Imp Cyl choke with matching numbers. Nothing else to say except-WOW!
